        "content": "<p>I have a question about an ambiguity in the statement of the Kock-Lawvere axiom on the nlab (<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Kock-Lawvere+axiom\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Kock-Lawvere+axiom</a>).</p>\n<p>The Kock-Lawvere axiom says under certain conditions on an algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>, we have that the obvious morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>W</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mrow><msub><mtext>Spec</mtext><mi>R</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>W</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">W \\to R^{\\textrm{Spec}_R(W)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord textrm mtight\">Spec</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2222em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.2341em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2659em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is an isomorphism.</p>\n<p>My question is: does this mean just an isomorphism in the ambient topos or an isomorphism of algebras? I.e., does the axiom require that the inverse is an algebra homomorphism? And if it does not, does it necessarily follow that it is?</p>",
